        "### Quantization: Scale, Zero-Point, and Calibration\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Scale and Zero-Point\n",
        "\n",
        "Quantization maps real-valued numbers to integers using two parameters:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Scale**: determines how much a single integer step represents in real value\n",
        "- **Zero-point**: the integer value that corresponds to real value 0\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "#### Why Do We Need Scale and Zero-Point?\n",
        "\n",
        "When we quantize a model, we want to map real values (floats) to a limited set of integers (e.g., int8: [-128, 127]).\n",
        "\n",
        "##### The Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose our data is:\n",
        "\n",
        "`x = [-1.0, ..., 2.0]`\n",
        "\n",
        "So the real range is:\n",
        "- from **-1.0 to 2.0** (range = 3.0)\n",
        "\n",
        "But the integer range is:\n",
        "- from **-128 to 127** (range = 255 values)\n",
        "\n",
        "We need to **map one range into the other**.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "##### Role of Scale → \"How much to compress\"\n",
        "\n",
        "We have to \"fit\" the real interval into the integer interval.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Real range = 3.0  \n",
        "- Integer range = 255  \n",
        "\n",
        "So each integer step should represent a small portion of the real range.\n",
        "\n",
        "👉 **Scale tells us how big one integer step is in real values**\n",
        "\n",
        "Without scale:\n",
        "- we wouldn't know how to convert between float and int\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "##### Problem Without Zero-Point\n",
        "\n",
        "If we only use scale, we might do:\n",
        "\n",
        "`q = x / scale`\n",
        "\n",
        "This forces:\n",
        "- `x = 0` → `q = 0`\n",
        "\n",
        "👉 But this is a problem!\n",
        "\n",
        "Our data is **not symmetric**:\n",
        "- min = -1.0\n",
        "- max = 2.0\n",
        "\n",
        "So:\n",
        "- zero is **not in the center** of the range\n",
        "\n",
        "If we force zero to map to 0:\n",
        "- we waste part of the integer range\n",
        "- we lose precision\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "##### Role of Zero-Point → \"Where to place zero\"\n",
        "\n",
        "👉 **Zero-point shifts the mapping so that the full integer range is used**\n",
        "\n",
        "Instead of forcing:\n",
        "- `0 → 0`\n",
        "\n",
        "we allow:\n",
        "- `0 → some integer value (zero_point)`\n",
        "\n",
        "This lets us:\n",
        "- map **min → -128**\n",
        "- map **max → 127**\n",
        "- and place zero **in the correct position in between**\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "The mapping is defined as:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Quantization (float → int):**  \n",
        "  `q = x / scale + zero_point`\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Dequantization (int → float):**  \n",
        "  `x = scale * (q - zero_point)`\n",
        "\n",
        "These parameters ensure that the numerical range of the original data is preserved as much as possible within the limited integer range.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Calibration\n",
        "\n",
        "Calibration is the process used to determine appropriate **scale** and **zero-point** values.\n",
        "\n",
        "- It is performed using a **representative dataset** (a small subset of real input data)\n",
        "- The model observes the range (min/max) of activations during inference\n",
        "- Based on these ranges, it computes quantization parameters that best approximate the original float distributions\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "XoM_yCxGOrCy"
      },
      "id": "XoM_yCxGOrCy"
